        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "After extensive use and testing, I believe I have gained a certain understanding of this issue, and therefore I have decided to provide some clarification:\r\n\r\n1. First, `vim.pack.add` does indeed install packages to the `opt` path by default; this is by design. In `init.lua`, I use `vim.pack.add()` to install the `nvim-lspconfig` plugin and configure `vim.lsp.enable()` for various file formats separately in the `ftplugin` path because I don't want to enable all LSP configurations indiscriminately for all file formats. The problem I encountered was that `vim.lsp.enable()` was ineffective. Using the command `:checkhealth vim.lsp`, I checked and found no Active Clients. However, when I placed the `nvim-lspconfig` package in the `start` path, the LSP started normally, and the defined LSPs appeared in Active Clients.\r\n\r\n2. I carefully read Evgeni Chasnovski's [article](https://echasnovski.com/blog/2026-03-13-a-guide-to-vim-pack) on `vim.pack` usage examples and found that the configuration for `nvim-lspconfig` always follows `vim.lsp.enable()`. I tried adding the `vim.pack.add` command to the configuration under the ftplugin path (like in the article, but not in `init.lua`), and the `lsp` was listed in Active Clients and worked correctly.\r\n\r\nI don't understand why separating it in my current configuration would cause `vim.lsp.enable()` to be ineffective. Am I doing something wrong? Any suggestions will be appreciated.",
            "created_at": "2026-05-29T17:11:48Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/neovim/nvim-lspconfig/pull/4364#issuecomment-4577852753",
